<!--Updating your starter file-->
<h3 id="update-your-starter-file">Update Your Starter File</h3>
<p>
    Follow these steps to make sure your <strong>FishTales</strong> starter file includes all the right report sites.
    Keeping this file accurate ensures FishTales can scrape and summarize reports correctly.
</p>
<div class="text-center">
    <ol class="text-start d-inline-block">
        <li class="mb-4">
            Run <strong>SiteScout</strong> to see if your starter file is missing any report sites.
            <img src="/images/docs/fish_tales/starter_file/new_site.png" alt="New Report Sites" class="img-fluid w-75 mx-auto d-block">
        </li>
        <li class="mb-4">
            For each new site, open it in your browser. Look for where reports are posted ‚Äî this might be a
            <em>Reports</em>, <em>Blog</em>, or <em>Fishing Updates</em> section.
            <img src="/images/docs/fish_tales/starter_file/arricks_home.png" alt="Arricks Home Page" class="img-fluid w-75 mx-auto d-block">
        </li>
        <li class="mb-4">
            Find the most recent report. Pay attention to the following while searching:
            <ul>
                <li>The date of the reports (to confirm the site still actively posts reports).</li>
                <li><strong>Keywords</strong> in the URL, such as <code>/fishing-reports/</code> or <code>/river-reports/</code>.</li>
                <li><strong>Junk words</strong> in the URL, such as <code>/page/</code> or <code>/category/</code>.</li>
                <li><strong>Click-phrases</strong> that signal new content, such as <code>Continue Reading</code> or <code>Read More</code>.</li>
            </ul>
            <em>Tip: If the latest report is older than 1‚Äì2 years, you may want to skip adding that site
            since it‚Äôs not actively updated.</em>
            <img src="/images/docs/fish_tales/starter_file/arricks_report_list.png" alt="Arricks Report List" class="img-fluid w-75 mx-auto d-block">
        </li>
        <li class="mb-4">
            Once you've located the report, inspect the page to figure out what part of the website contains the report text:
            <ul class="mb-0">
                <li>Right-click on the report and choose <strong>Inspect</strong> (or <strong>Inspect Element</strong>).</li>
                <li>Keyboard shortcuts:
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Windows/Linux:</strong> <code>Ctrl + Shift + I</code> or <code>F12</code></li>
                        <li><strong>Mac:</strong> <code>Cmd + Option + I</code> or <code>F12</code></li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>In the inspector:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Hover over different HTML elements to see which part of the page they highlight.</li>
                        <li>Or use the <strong>element picker</strong> (the cursor icon in the inspector toolbar) to click directly on the report text in the page.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Look for the container around the report text ‚Äî for example:
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>&lt;article&gt;</code></li>
                        <li><code>&lt;div class="post"&gt;</code></li>
                        <li>Or another clear element that only holds the report content.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <img src="/images/docs/fish_tales/starter_file/arricks_report.png" alt="Arricks Report" class="img-fluid w-75 mx-auto d-block">
        </li>

        <li class="mb-4">
            Fill out the starter file with what you‚Äôve found:
            <ul>
                <li>Put <strong>keywords</strong>, <strong>junk-words</strong>, and <strong>click-phrases</strong> into their columns.</li>
                <li>Enter the <strong>selector</strong> you found (so FishTales knows where the report text lives).</li>
                <li>Optionally, add the date of the last report you saw in the <strong>Last Updated</strong> column (for your own tracking).</li>
            </ul>
            <img src="/images/docs/fish_tales/starter_file/updated_starter_file.png" alt="Updated Starter File" class="img-fluid w-75 mx-auto d-block">
        </li>
    </ol>
</div>


<h5 id="advanced-selectors">Advanced Selectors</h5>
<p>
    Most of the time, you can use a simple selector like <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> or <code>div.post</code> to capture the report content. These are easier to maintain and less likely to break if the website changes.
</p>
<p>
    Sometimes, a site doesn‚Äôt use clear containers, and you‚Äôll need a more <strong>advanced selector</strong> to target the report. For example:
</p>
<pre><code>div.entry-content:has(p:text-matches("Fishing Report", "i"))</code></pre>
<p>
    This means: ‚Äúlook for a <code>div</code> with the class <code>entry-content</code> that contains a paragraph mentioning ‚ÄòFishing Report‚Äô (ignoring upper/lower case).‚Äù
</p>
<p>
    Advanced selectors can feel complicated, but don‚Äôt worry ‚Äî you don‚Äôt need to start from scratch. Check the <a href="/example_files/fishTales_starter_file.xlsx" download>example starter file</a> included with FishTales for working examples you can build on.
</p>
<p>
    Tips for advanced selectors:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Try simple selectors first. Only use advanced ones if you can‚Äôt capture the report otherwise.</li>
    <li>Test your selector in the browser console to make sure it highlights only the report text.</li>
    <li>If you get stuck, tools like <strong>GPT</strong> or <strong>Gemini</strong> can help you write or debug a selector.</li>
    <li>Keep notes in your starter file so you remember why you used a particular selector.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    Used carefully, advanced selectors let FishTales capture reports even from tricky websites.
</p>

